notes_en:
Competition festivities of the Rural Association of Nurmes:
The best marksman shot to 15 centimeters; a 54-naula weight was lifted 50 times; in väkikiven nosto (lifting the väkikivi) 47 leiviskä were raised; 340 meters were run in 54 seconds; the best high jump reached 63 inches. These results—among others—prove that “there is still strength in Finland, men and manliness.”

The women, too, had their competition. They were blindfolded with a cloth and then given scissors with which they were to cut a thread hanging from a stake, to which the prize was attached. It was amusing to watch, but at the same time it brought to mind the position of women in former and present days: for a woman, it seems, is still guided only by blind fate—one must simply stumble forward, whether one reaches the goal or not. While men must sharpen their reason, their eyes, and all their other powers, women are required merely to gape like a sack-headed simpleton.

Shooting:
1st prize, 20 mk: Antti Koukkari, 15 cm;
2nd, 12 mk: Juho Kiiskinen, 17 cm;
3rd, 8 mk: clerk K. E. Turunen, 20 cm;
4th, 4 mk: student K. Relander, 24 cm.

Lifting the väkikivi:
1st prize, 1 mk 50 p: Pekka Tolonen, lifted 47 L8;
2nd, 1 mk: Olli Moilanen, lifted 47 L2;
3rd, 50 p: Taavi Tinnonen, lifted 44 L8.

Weight lifting:
1st prize, 1 mk 50 p: Olli Tolvanen, lifted 54 naulaa 50 times;
2nd, 1 mk: Pekka Newalainen, lifted the same 26 times;
3rd, 50 p: Wille Piironen, lifted the same 13 times.

High jump:
1st prize, 1 mk 50 p: F. Sikanen, 63 inches;
2nd, 1 mk: A. Rantanen, 60 inches;
3rd, 50 p: M. Puoskari, very young, 45 inches.

Shot put:
1st prize, 1 mk 50 p: Pekka Newalainen, threw a 16-naula shot 36 feet;
2nd, 1 mk: Olli Tolvanen, 32 feet;
3rd, 50 p: Olli Eskelinen, 32 feet.

Long jump:
1st prize, 1 mk: T. Sikanen, 14½ feet;
3rd prize, 50 p: P. Newalainen, 14 feet.

